div.p:
                     V. 13. A watcher and an holy One, Eir vecaddish, where Eir, which signifies a Watcher, the Seventy render an Angel. And an Angel is called Eir, or a Watcher, because they being not clogged with drowzy and dull flesh and bloud, but having more fiery and etherial bodies, they are never drowned in sleep, as we mortals are. And they are also called Watchers from their Office or Ministry, they watching over the affairs of men. But whereas there is added, vecaddish, and an holy One, the Particle [
                        〈☐〉
                     ] will be

better rendred [that is to say] an holy One, viz. an holy Angel; To whose care the affairs of mankind, especially of the Church of God, are committed. There was the like sense of [
                        〈☐〉
                     ] v. 9.
